                <li>
                    <h4 class="bio">Kimberlee Poole</h4>
                    <p>“If I can stop one heart from breaking,<br/>
                        I shall not live in vain; <br/>
                        If I can ease one life the aching, <br/>
                        Or cool one pain, <br/>
                        Or help one fainting robin <br/>
                        Unto his nest again, <br/>
                        I shall not live in vain.” –Emily Dickenson</p>
                        <p></p>
                        <p>My name is Kimmee and I am many things. I am a daughter. I am a sister. I am an aunt. I am a student. I am a musician. I am a poet. I am an artist. I am a photographer. I am a writer. I am a drama geek. But two of the most important things I am are first a child of God and second a volunteer at Crossroads Farm. I work at Crossroads because I feel a strong leading in my life from God to work with the youth of the rural community. As a former student of CRF I have experienced firsthand the difference it can make in the lives of students. Seeing God work in the lives of students has been one of the most amazing experiences in my life.</p>
                </li>
                <li class="odd"><h4 class="bio">Mike Richardson</h4>
                <p>Hi my name is Mike, husband to Connie. Outside of work and CRF, my hobbies include running and fishing. My involvement with Crossroads started several years ago. I first become aware of CRF from my oldest child who attended program nights and special outreach activities. I believe God has placed Connie and me with CRF and can tell you that I feel blessed to be a part of the ministry. Not only am I able to assist in helping kids come to know Christ but find the ministry helps in my growth too.</p>
                <p></p>
                <p>God has a way of connecting people together. I have had the good fortune of several great friendships with students, several of which I still keep in contact with long after they have graduated. CRF is a needed ministry in Hillsdale County and I am fortunate to be a part of it.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <h4 class="bio">Connie Richardson</h4>
                    <p>Hi, my name is Connie.  I have volunteered with CRF, along with my husband, for the past 8 years.  I love the color yellow, and I love smiley faces!  My favorite Bible verse is Philippians 4:13 "I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me."  Sometimes I take on too much, and I hang on that verse, and you know what, He always gets me through!!  I love working with the teens through CRF.  I feel God has led me there, with the help of Doug and Dawn!  I had always prayed that I wanted to go on a mission trip (which someday I will!) and God brought this to me, and after a few years, I realized that yes, this is it for now, right here in my own community!  I pray that God continue to use me to plant the seeds, and to help nurture these delicate young women to stay in God's light, accept Him, and live out Godly lives that He so desires.  I've always told my own children, and I repeat it to "my girls" in my care cell, "do unto others as you would want done to you"  Matthew 7:12.  So, I try to live this out.  That's why I love the color yellow (it's warm, it's like a sunshiney day, it makes me smile).  So, give God your burdens, and start smiling!!!!!</p>
                </li>
